This wasn’t targeted by coalition planes, but a cell called Khorasan - hand-picked by Al-Qaeda leader Ayman al-Zawahiri and thought to be on the brink of attempting to blow up Western civilian airlines - was bombed.

Counter-terrorism police think that the two groups may have been working alongside each other and that the Britons were being drilled by Khorasan  to carry out suicide attacks on Western targets, according to The Times.

Kamara’s mother, Khadijah, 35, said that he had secretly travelled to the war-torn country and she felt ‘numb’ that he was dead.

The teenager, who called himself Khalil al-Britani, had recently completed a resit of his GCSEs at Varndean College in Brighton.

His single mother and her three other sons, who live in the Sussex city, are believed to be refugees from Sierra Leone who came to Britain via the Netherlands.

